17
00:02:10,908 --> 00:02:12,268
I said, or a cannabis shop.

18
00:02:12,308 --> 00:02:13,189
He said, exactly.

19
00:02:13,749 --> 00:02:19,894
So, that's really what started and was the impetus to me gathering some neighbors together.

20
00:02:19,954 --> 00:02:21,035
What do you think of this?

21
00:02:21,295 --> 00:02:22,416
Are you concerned?

22
00:02:22,596 --> 00:02:23,737
What are we going to do about it?

23
00:02:25,818 --> 00:02:26,238
Okay.

24
00:02:27,599 --> 00:02:28,360
Good answer.

25
00:02:28,940 --> 00:02:36,506
So, the follow-up to that would be, I guess, why don't you think the city is doing the right things?

26
00:02:36,926 --> 00:02:38,728
Why wouldn't they want to do the right things?

27
00:02:40,500 --> 00:02:46,622
Well, I think it's probably a couple of possibilities and maybe a combination, a little bit of everything.

28
00:02:46,642 --> 00:02:58,866
I think that the administration has their own agenda from the mayor all the way down to the city council members, the community development board, zoning, and just the list goes on.

29
00:02:59,646 --> 00:03:02,747
None of them in particular seem to have

30
00:03:03,487 --> 00:03:09,515
significant business experience, which is really there's processes involved.

31
00:03:09,535 --> 00:03:12,018
You get experience with how things should be managed.

32
00:03:12,398 --> 00:03:17,925
And their experience really for the city council consists of someone with a theater major.

33
00:03:18,526 --> 00:03:25,835
someone that couldn't get elected in Somerville, so they moved to Medford, and then they were elected to the City Council.

34
00:03:25,955 --> 00:03:32,503
You have someone on the City Council that has worked with some nonprofits and managed to bankrupt one of them.

35
00:03:32,523 --> 00:03:36,528
And you have a lot of career students.

36
00:03:37,028 --> 00:03:42,969
with very limited life experience and no business experience as it stands.

37
00:03:43,570 --> 00:03:46,730
They think of the people of Medford are not paying attention.

38
00:03:46,930 --> 00:03:52,012
And up until some of the recent things that have been happening throughout the city, that is probably very true.

39
00:03:52,472 --> 00:03:53,872
People became complacent.

40
00:03:54,332 --> 00:03:56,333
And look at the meetings.

41
00:03:56,933 --> 00:04:02,494
Our city council meetings are consumed with they all vote in a pack.

42
00:04:03,114 --> 00:04:06,655
They look at their historical trend of how they vote.

43
00:04:07,675 --> 00:04:11,916
There's only one outlier on the city council, and that's George Scarpelli.

44
00:04:12,376 --> 00:04:14,797
Other than that, you have six members.

45
00:04:15,217 --> 00:04:16,677
They all seem to vote alike.

46
00:04:16,797 --> 00:04:19,478
And you and I both know you can walk out there on the street.

47
00:04:19,498 --> 00:04:24,119
You're not going to get five people that agree on the color of the sky, what the temperature is.

48
00:04:24,439 --> 00:04:27,260
And yet, sadly enough, they all vote together.

49
00:04:27,900 --> 00:04:29,500
And they ran on a slate.

50
00:04:29,860 --> 00:04:35,502
I think they agreed behind closed doors, from what I've heard, that they all vote in a pact.

51
00:04:35,662 --> 00:04:36,702
And so that's what they're doing.

52
00:04:37,222 --> 00:04:45,464
And unfortunately, what that causes is we have lost democracy on our city council.

53
00:04:45,864 --> 00:04:47,765
This is not the democratic way.

54
00:04:48,365 --> 00:04:50,606
You should be having discussions.

55
00:04:50,646 --> 00:04:57,508
You should be having three and four people against and for something and arguing and having in-depth conversations.

56
00:04:57,968 --> 00:04:59,188
And we just don't have it.

57
00:04:59,708 --> 00:05:01,989
And one of the city councilors,

58
00:05:02,829 --> 00:05:07,992
just a few weeks ago, Collins said, we are elected to make decisions for you.

59
00:05:08,373 --> 00:05:10,014
No, that is not correct.

60
00:05:10,374 --> 00:05:20,140
You are elected to represent us and vote how we as constituents and taxpayers would want the vote to go.

61
00:05:22,021 --> 00:05:23,482
You know, excellent answers.

62
00:05:23,982 --> 00:05:24,342
Really.

63
00:05:24,443 --> 00:05:26,944
I mean, that's like it was perfect.

64
00:05:27,144 --> 00:05:28,045
I mean, the truth.

65
00:05:29,055 --> 00:05:31,336
Love it, and thank you for that response.

66
00:05:31,496 --> 00:05:36,698
I think it's something people need to hear, that people need to understand.

67
00:05:37,258 --> 00:05:39,019
So thank you for that response.

68
00:05:40,640 --> 00:05:41,420
Well spoken.

69
00:05:42,060 --> 00:05:54,746
So now I want to get into what can be done to correct the problems Method is having, and what are your suggestions?

70
00:05:55,046 --> 00:05:57,827
What's some of the solutions maybe, or what are your suggestions?

71
00:05:58,941 --> 00:06:12,294
So initially we went old school with standouts and this and that and the other thing and trying to go to the city council meetings and voice our opinions and it became very apparent that that isn't what they wanted to hear.

72
00:06:12,374 --> 00:06:15,537
So I think right now we are in the throes of

73
00:06:16,318 --> 00:06:17,058
legal action.

74
00:06:17,698 --> 00:06:25,941
I started reaching out to attorneys that I know to have conversations to start to figure out what are our legal options?

75
00:06:26,001 --> 00:06:27,461
Do we have legal options?

76
00:06:28,501 --> 00:06:33,303
And sadly, through the methadone experience, I quickly learned that they don't care what you think.

77
00:06:34,564 --> 00:06:41,631
And so, you know, people were completely blindsided with the fact that we were going to get a methadone dispensary.

78
00:06:42,471 --> 00:06:47,756
We gathered 550 signatures against the methadone dispensary.

79
00:06:48,037 --> 00:06:49,278
And that was gathered quickly.

80
00:06:49,478 --> 00:06:51,139
That was gathered quickly in weeks.

81
00:06:51,279 --> 00:06:54,520
We were running behind the eight ball with everything on that one.

82
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:57,360
We were working weekends.

83
00:06:57,740 --> 00:07:01,141
And then it came time to show up to the final city council meeting.

84
00:07:01,642 --> 00:07:07,823
And we sent out emails and all the people that had been at the standouts, which was very obvious.

85
00:07:07,883 --> 00:07:11,965
People were pulling their cars over going, where is this methadone dispensary going?

86
00:07:12,125 --> 00:07:12,605
Right here.

87
00:07:13,045 --> 00:07:15,107
Well, there's a school 0.2 miles away.

88
00:07:15,367 --> 00:07:16,248
They couldn't believe it.

89
00:07:17,288 --> 00:07:18,589
How come we haven't heard of this?

90
00:07:18,970 --> 00:07:23,653
We even had people on West Medford signing our petition.

91
00:07:23,693 --> 00:07:27,016
And I said to one woman, I said, why are you signing our petition?

92
00:07:27,056 --> 00:07:28,457
This doesn't really affect you.

93
00:07:28,737 --> 00:07:30,038
She goes, it's Medford.

94
00:07:30,499 --> 00:07:31,600
We're all Medford.

95
00:07:31,740 --> 00:07:36,143
It affects all of us, right, for the city and how we are perceived.

96
00:07:36,704 --> 00:07:36,904
And so

97
00:07:38,485 --> 00:07:40,928
Everyone showed up at that city council meeting.

98
00:07:41,148 --> 00:07:42,329
Everyone was ready to voice.

99
00:07:42,629 --> 00:07:46,353
We had filled that gallery and we were shut down.

100
00:07:46,733 --> 00:07:51,077
The city council president, Zach Baer, said we will not be taking public comment.

101
00:07:51,458 --> 00:07:52,459
People were in outrage.

102
00:07:52,619 --> 00:07:55,262
I was worried somebody was going to go actually over the rails.

103
00:07:57,143 --> 00:07:58,144
It was that bad.

104
00:07:58,744 --> 00:08:03,126
And so George Scarpelli got a break, and they went in the back.

105
00:08:03,206 --> 00:08:08,508
And I think he said, you know, this is not going to be good for any of us if we don't let the people that came here to speak.

106
00:08:08,888 --> 00:08:13,410
Sadly, the majority of people had already left because they were just so frustrated.

107
00:08:13,810 --> 00:08:23,855
And I felt bad because I said, listen, if you really feel this strongly about the methadone dispensary in the neighborhood that close to a school, then please, show up.

108
00:08:24,575 --> 00:08:26,722
Tell them, I can't be the only voice.

109
00:08:27,103 --> 00:08:28,848
Ten of us can't be the only voice.

110
00:08:31,663 --> 00:08:34,485
Anyway, you know, they were just outraged.

111
00:08:34,625 --> 00:08:42,272
And George eventually got them to, who was left in the gallery, be able to come up and speak and things like that.

112
00:08:43,453 --> 00:08:50,238
And the reason I think people felt so strongly is that this Habit OpCo is really a company of bad actors.

113
00:08:50,738 --> 00:08:53,701
They have a long, long list of complaints.

114
00:08:54,001 --> 00:08:55,843
Every city that they have gone into.

115
00:08:56,843 --> 00:09:02,128
and every city that they manage from Lynn to Springfield, they're up in arms.

116
00:09:02,188 --> 00:09:07,173
And because they purchase the buildings, they really, they have, they're property owners.

117
00:09:07,273 --> 00:09:15,380
So there isn't anything that the city is going to do except ask them and they very vehemently say, you know, too bad we own the building.

118
00:09:16,501 --> 00:09:18,303
This same company recently,

119
00:09:18,663 --> 00:09:32,148
had an article written in the New York Times that there's a federal investigation going against them because they also own inpatient clinics for mental health and bipolar and things like that.

120
00:09:32,449 --> 00:09:40,912
And they were found, even the employees are testifying against them in the federal investigation and the federal lawsuit, that they hold people against their will.

121
00:09:41,172 --> 00:09:47,134
If you have the right kind of insurance, they're able to figure out that they're going to get paid, so they hold you against your will.

122
00:09:48,675 --> 00:09:58,983
I think that's really sad, and I think that fortunately we dodged a bullet by not letting that company into the parameters of our city.

123
00:09:59,543 --> 00:10:17,117
And one of the things that was so interesting in a lot of the research, our government, the Health and Human Services Division, went on to say and has done research around the methadone dispensaries, and there's a huge increase in human trafficking and

124
00:10:17,597 --> 00:10:27,786
things like that, and sex trafficking of children around those areas, which, you know, so close to an elementary school, it just makes me shudder to think that.

125
00:10:28,427 --> 00:10:40,177
And it was then that I decided, after all of that, that really legal action was the only course that we could have where we were going to get the results that we needed immediately.

126
00:10:41,899 --> 00:10:42,559
Sounds great.

127
00:10:44,892 --> 00:10:47,553
I agree with what you're saying, makes sense.

128
00:10:49,694 --> 00:11:05,920
I guess one of the things I think people listening would love to know about is, and I don't know how specific can you be, but can you be more specific on the legal actions being taken on behalf of the people in Method?

129
00:11:07,901 --> 00:11:13,422
So legal actions, unfortunately, did not just end with the methadone dispensary.

130
00:11:13,502 --> 00:11:24,585
Legal action and having a legal guidance, if you will, and an attorney on retainer is something that we continue with to this day.

131
00:11:25,165 --> 00:11:36,968
We believe that is our only avenue currently with this administration to really push back around if there's large numbers of people that are seeing things that they don't want.

132
00:11:38,028 --> 00:11:48,816
And the reason we have to do that is, think about it, the mayor hasn't had a solicitor in this town for three years, I believe.

133
00:11:50,687 --> 00:11:55,052
It's because the people have no legal guidance.

134
00:11:55,212 --> 00:11:59,517
Typically, you would be able to go to the city solicitor and say, this is what's happening.

135
00:11:59,917 --> 00:12:00,578
What do you think?

136
00:12:00,938 --> 00:12:09,868
But because we don't have that, we have no guidance for the community and for independent people to ask questions and confirm.

137
00:12:12,390 --> 00:12:26,709
She has then engaged a law firm that has allegiance to her because she's paying them, rightfully so, and now she can do whatever she wants, wherever she wants, and we are forced to live with it.

138
00:12:27,350 --> 00:12:28,992
Basically, she has carte blanche.

139
00:12:30,173 --> 00:12:45,340
And she's banking on the fact, and I believe, my opinion, that we don't have the wherewithal and we don't have the financial capacity to hire a law firm, a good law firm, a big Boston law firm that will represent us.

140
00:12:47,881 --> 00:12:48,221
We do.

141
00:12:48,742 --> 00:12:49,262
And we have.

142
00:12:50,263 --> 00:12:57,688
And while we do have the same law firm that represented us with the methadone dispensary, we have a different attorney.

143
00:12:57,868 --> 00:13:13,078
And we did that intentionally because the attorney that we now have has a municipality expertise and specialty, which is, we feel, something that we really needed going forward with some of the things that are going on in Medford currently.

144
00:13:14,359 --> 00:13:16,101
And he's gone up against KP Law.

145
00:13:17,201 --> 00:13:24,005
Our newest fight, as I'm sure you're aware, is the Salem Street debacle that's going on.

146
00:13:25,286 --> 00:13:36,952
And so he was able to put together and pen a very nice but strong legal letter as to why this shouldn't be taking place on Salem Street.

147
00:13:38,140 --> 00:13:40,821
Yeah, we know all about Salem Street.

